<div id="comment_status_43594597" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_43594597" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_43594597" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_43594597" name="comment_link_43594597" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3703395&amp;cid=43594597" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(43594597)" >Re:Remember the old adage</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_43594597" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 43594597); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~petermgreen">petermgreen</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~petermgreen">(876956)</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_43594597">		 &lt;<a href="mailto:plugwashNO%40SPAMp10link.net">plugwashNO@SPAMp10link.net</a>&gt;
		on Tuesday April 30, 2013 @04:42PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3703395&amp;cid=43594597">#43594597</a>)
		<small><a href="http://www.p10link.net/plugwash/" title="http://www.p10link.net/plugwash/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_43594597"><p>Bitcoin mining is starting to move towards ASICs now.</p><p>But ignoring that even with FPGA while the FPGAs themselves are standard parts the boards usually aren't. Afaict most off the shelf boards for FPGAs fall into one of two categroies. Either they are PCIe/PXIe cards designed to move a lot of data over a bus system or they are hardware dev boards with loads of different interfaces for a developer to play with. Bitcoin mining needs neither of those, it just needs power and a way to get a tiny ammount of data in and out.  The result is an off the shelf FPGA board is a poor value proposition for mining and a mining optimised FPGA board isn't much use for anything else.</p><p>I guess you could desolder the FPGAs from your no longer viable FPGA boards and then reball them and try and sell them but I think you'd find it pretty hard to find a buyer for such parts (afaict reballing voids the warranty) and if you did find one you'd have to sell them at a massive discount to fresh FPGAs from the manufacturer.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_43594597">
<span class="ind"></span><a class="btn link" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3703395&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;cid=43593211" onclick="return D2.selectParent(43593211)">Parent</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
