</li></ul></li><li id="tree_43593695" class="comment oneline"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_43593695" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_43593695" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_43593695" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_43593695" name="comment_link_43593695" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3703395&amp;cid=43593695" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(43593695)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_43593695" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 43593695); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~lgw">lgw</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~lgw">(121541)</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_43593695"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_43593695"><p>There's a related problem here I think people are overlooking.  Part of the appeal of bitcoin is it's decentralized nature - a government can't easily stop transfer of bitcoins between individuals.  However, since mining is transaction processing, if it becomes only profitable to do transaction processing in the 3 biggest miner's datacenters, we're back to centralization and therefore easy government control.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_43593695">

</div>
